  "english_translation": {
    "entry_translation": "Sūrat Yūsuf.\n\nMakkan. Its counterpart (naẓīrah) in the two Madani counts, the Makki count, and the Shami count is Sūrat al-Anbiyāʾ; in the Kufi count it is Sūrat Subḥān; and in the Basri count it is Sūrat al-Kahf and Sūrat al-Anbiyāʾ. Its words are one thousand and seventy-six, and its letters are seven thousand and forty-three. It is one hundred and eleven verses, with no disagreement in it.\n\nIn it there are, by consensus, four places that resemble verse-endings without being counted: “minhunna sikkīnan”, “maʿahu l-sijna fatayān”, “yaʾti baṣīran”, and “ʿibratan li-ulī l-albāb”.",
    "ruus_note": "The ordinal_madani_2_baseline field gives the recovered later-Madani sequence. In the transmitted witness, the opening head “الْمُبين” is unnumbered, the block then runs with displayed numerals 1–110, displayed 68 is parsed as “يعْمل ون” and normalized only for internal spacing to “يعْملون”, and the witness ends with a blank terminal display-total line “١١ - ١”. The structured data therefore treats the displayed numerals as witness metadata rather than as the primary ordinal layer."
  },
